Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Inventory

| Line | API | Pattern |
|------|-----|---------|
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `Thread.Interrupt` | Blocking call interruption — wake from `WaitOne` |
| `_thread.Abort()` | `Thread.Abort` | Timeout enforcement — kill after 5s grace |
| `while (true)` | Loop | Cancellable work loop — no exit condition |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny wakes on either a new event OR cancellation —
            // replaces Thread.Interrupt for waking blocked threads.
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items — fixes a race in the original
            // where multiple Enqueue calls before Reset caused items
            // to be skipped.
            List<string> items;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                items = new List<string>(_queue);
                _queue.Clear();
            }

            foreach (var item in items)
            {
                if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                    break;
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals the token → wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait up to 5s for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation — replaces `Thread.Interrupt` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancel signals the token's `WaitHandle`, waking `WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The cooperative loop exits cleanly, so the fallback kill is unnecessary |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter-weight; avoids kernel object when uncontended |

## Pitfalls to Watch

1. **`Handle()` must be short or check the token** — cancellation only takes effect at the next `WaitAny` call. If `Handle()` runs for minutes, `Stop()` will block. Pass the token into `Handle()` if it does heavy work.

2. **Original race condition fixed** — the old code called `Reset()` then `Dequeue()` one item. If two `Enqueue` calls happened before `Reset`, the second item was lost until the next signal. The new code drains the entire queue.

3. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable` and leaks timer/callback resources if not disposed. The new class implements `IDisposable` for this reason.

4. **No forced kill exists in .NET 8** — if `Handle()` truly hangs on uncooperative code, the only option is to move that work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort`.
